{"timestamp": "2025-12-06 22:11:08.485469", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting Diagnosis Report\n\nScope and baseline\n- Topology: Multi-area OSPF core and distribution with bridged access, centralized DHCP and DNS in server farm 10.200.0.0/24. Hosts on 10.<core>.<dist>.0/24. Nginx load balancer published as web99.local; Apache web servers web0.local…web3.local. OSPF advertises all infra and server subnets end-to-end.\n- Key endpoints examined: host_1_1_1_1 (10.1.1.11) and host_2_1_1_1 (10.2.1.10), DHCP server (10.200.0.8), DNS server (10.200.0.2), load balancer (10.200.0.7), router_dist_2_1.\n\nFindings\n1) End-to-end health from 10.1.1.0/24 is normal\n- host_1_1_1_1 -> DNS (10.200.0.2), load_balancer (10.200.0.7), web_server_0 (10.200.0.3) all ping OK with low latency (rtt avg ~2–5 ms, occasional spikes typical for lab).\n- host_1_1_1_1 HTTP tests:\n  - curl http://web99.local total ~1.08–1.13 s, TTFB ~0.28–0.32 s.\n  - curl http://web0.local total ~1.01–1.20 s, TTFB ~0.20–0.40 s.\n- host_1_1_1_1 routing received via DHCP:\n  - ip route: default via 10.1.1.1 dev eth0; 10.1.1.0/24 on-link. This matches DHCP scope and distribution SVI addressing for that subnet.\nConclusion: Routing, DNS, and web services are reachable and performant from 10.1.1.0/24.\n\n2) Severe connectivity issue in subnet 10.2.1.0/24\n- host_2_1_1_1 IP/DHCP state:\n  - IP: 10.2.1.10/24 (dynamic), resolv.conf: nameserver 10.200.0.2.\n  - DHCP lease (multiple entries) shows option routers 10.2.1.254; option domain-name-servers 10.200.0.2.\n  - ip route shows only the connected route: 10.2.1.0/24 dev eth0; there is no default route installed.\n- Ping tests from host_2_1_1_1:\n  - To local SVI 10.2.1.1: OK (rtt ~1 ms).\n  - To configured gateway 10.2.1.254: Destination Host Unreachable from 10.2.1.10 (no ARP/gateway present).\n  - To DNS 10.200.0.2: Destination Host Unreachable (no default route).\n- Ping tests to host_2_1_1_1 from DNS timed out. Explanation: even if the packet arrives to the host, the host’s reply would need to be routed off-subnet; with an invalid default gateway (10.2.1.254 not present), the host cannot send the reply, so ping fails.\nImpact: host_2_1_1_1 cannot reach any off-subnet resources (DNS, server farm, other VLANs). All hosts in 10.2.1.0/24 would be similarly affected.\n\n3) Distribution router for 10.2.1.0/24 is healthy but uses a different SVI address than DHCP advertises\n- router_dist_2_1 interface and routing:\n  - br0 SVI address: 10.2.1.1/24 (not .254).\n  - OSPF running, advertising 10.2.1.0/24; has OSPF routes to 10.200.0.0/24 and other subnets via core (172.16.0.10 neighbor).\n  - show ip route confirms reachability to server farm and other user subnets; local subnet 10.2.1.0/24 is connected.\n- DHCP server configuration (/etc/dhcp/dhcpd.conf):\n  - Subnet 10.2.1.0/24 provides option routers 10.2.1.254.\n  - Other subnets match their distribution gateway at .1 (e.g., 10.1.1.0/24 uses 10.1.1.1; 10.1.2.0/24 uses 10.1.2.1), which aligns with working hosts.\nConclusion: There is a configuration mismatch specifically for 10.2.1.0/24: DHCP offers a non-existent default gateway (10.2.1.254) while the actual distribution SVI is 10.2.1.1.\n\nAnomaly detection\n- Anomaly: Hosts in 10.2.1.0/24 receive an invalid default gateway via DHCP, causing absence of a default route and loss of connectivity to any off-subnet destinations (including DNS and web services).\n- Evidence:\n  - host_2_1_1_1 ip route lacks default route; dhclient.leases shows option routers 10.2.1.254.\n  - DHCP scope for 10.2.1.0/24 specifies option routers 10.2.1.254.\n  - router_dist_2_1 SVI is 10.2.1.1; 10.2.1.254 is not present/reachable (host cannot ARP it; ping fails).\n  - Inbound ping from DNS to host_2_1_1_1 times out, consistent with host’s inability to reply off-subnet due to the wrong gateway.\n\nFault localization\n- Faulty component(s): DHCP server configuration for subnet 10.2.1.0/24 and/or the addressing plan for router_dist_2_1. The distribution router is configured at 10.2.1.1; the DHCP server is advertising 10.2.1.254. One of these is wrong, and the mismatch breaks host routing.\n- Non-faulty components: OSPF adjacency and routing in the core and distribution appear healthy; server farm services (DNS, LB, web servers) are responsive from correctly configured subnets; L2 access for 10.2.1.0/24 is operational (host can reach SVI 10.2.1.1).\n\nRoot cause\n- Root cause: Misconfigured default gateway in the DHCP scope for 10.2.1.0/24 (option routers 10.2.1.254), which does not correspond to the actual default gateway address on router_dist_2_1 (10.2.1.1). This results in hosts not installing or using a valid default route, preventing any inter-subnet communication.\n\nAdditional observations\n- DHCP lease times are set very short (default 30 s, max 60 s). While not the cause of the outage, this induces frequent renewals (observed valid_lft ~29 s) and may contribute to churn but did not cause reachability loss here.\n- Minor ICMP/HTTP latency spikes observed are within typical lab variance and not indicative of a systemic performance issue.\n\nOverall assessment\n- The OSPF routing domain and server farm are healthy.\n- Connectivity is normal from the 10.1.1.0/24 segment.\n- The 10.2.1.0/24 user segment is effectively isolated from the rest of the network due to a DHCP default gateway/gateway addressing mismatch.", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 14359, "output_tokens": 5114, "total_tokens": 19473, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 11392}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 3456}}}
